   "source": [
    "# LSTM Calibration of a Low-Cost PM₂.₅ Sensor\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook calibrates a low-cost PM₂.₅ sensor against a reference instrument using an LSTM.\n",
    "It walks from raw sensor logs to a calibrated output, and reports how well the calibration does on the **validation** and **test** sets (R², MAE, RMSE) with scatter plots. The code is based on the work presented in the paper by \n",
    "Sengupta, Arindam, et al. \"A temporal deep learning framework for calibration of low-cost air quality sensors.\" arXiv preprint arXiv:2604.21527 (2026).\"\n",
    "\n",
    "**Two ways to run it** (pick one in Section 7):\n",
    "- **Option A — Train from scratch:** fits the LSTM on your data.\n",
    "- **Option B — Load pretrained weights:** skips training and loads a saved weights file.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What you need:** the 3 feather (`.ftr`) data files listed in Section 1, sitting next to this notebook. These are the baseline corrected files.
    "\n",
    "**Pipeline order:** load data → engineer features → build the model table → scale + window + split → train *or* load weights → evaluate on val/test.\n",
    "\n",
    "**REQUIREMENTS:**\n",
    "Python: 3.9.18,\n",
    "NumPy: 1.26.4,\n",
    "Pandas: 2.2.2,\n",
    "Matplotlib: 3.9.0,\n",
    "scikit-learn: 1.5.0,\n",
    "TensorFlow / Keras : 2.10.0\n",
    "\n",
    "**Raw Sensor Dataset:** https://ora.ox.ac.uk/objects/uuid:66fbe8c1-4b63-4124-bf0d-a78cbc9e1408"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f1f6c30f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
